indigenous cultures and existing religious traditions. These traditions have inevitably influenced the ways in which Buddhist ideas and practices have been understood and adapted. Tracing the branches and fruits of these culturally specific transmissions and adaptations is as fascinating as it is challenging.Women in Buddhist Traditions chronicles pivotal moments in the history of Buddhist women, from the beginning of Buddhist history until today. The book highlights the unique contributions of Buddhist women from a variety of backgrounds and the strategies they have developed to challenge patriarchy in the process of creating an enlightened society.Women in Buddhist Traditions offers a groundbreaking and insightful introduction to the lives of Buddhist women world-wide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBuddhist women. 0aWomen in Buddhism. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / History.2bisacsh  aBhikkhuni.  aBuddhist acculturation.  aBuddhist activism.  aBuddhist cultures.  aBuddhist feminism.  aBuddhist nuns.  aChina.  aEngaged Buddhism.  aMahāprajāpatī.  aMongolian Buddhism.  aPatriarchy.  aSaṅghamittā.  aSouth Asia.  aSoutheast Asia.  aTibetan Buddhism.  aTibetan diaspora.  aWestern Buddhism.  abhikkhuni lineage.  abhikkhuni ordination.  abhikkhunī saṅgha.  acultural adaptation.  afemale renunciants.  afeminism.  afeminist reflection.  agender anthropology.  agender equity.  ageshe degree.  amonastic life.  amonastic ordination.  anuns.  aordination lineage.  aordination lineages.  areligious legitimacy.  areligious women.  arenunciant women.  asocial activism.  asocial engagement.  astructural injustice.  avinaya.  awomen practitioners.  awomen’s activism.  awomen’s history.  awomen’s movements.  awomen’s ordination.08iTitle is part of e